Hey, I've been investigating this all day today and all of the past weekend. It turns out there is an issue with the bitsandbytes library which leads to a memory leak when you delete and reload a model that has Stable Embeddings. This means that overtime the GPU RAM gets filled up when you're constantly reloading such a model.

I've raised this as an issue with the btisandbytes team here: https://github.com/bitsandbytes-foundation/bitsandbytes/issues/1462 and in the meantime am working on a fix for this for our subnet here: https://github.com/KMFODA/DistributedTraining/tree/fix/oom_on_reload. I plan to test this PR for a bit and if it succeeds in mitigating the issue merge it for all to use.

If testing isn't succesfull in 1-2 days then I'll remove the StableEmbeddings from the model. I'm reluctant to do so as a first step as it has been really improving convergence of the model's loss over time.

1. Deleting the weights of all Stable Embeddings layers before reloading the model state to prevent the memory leak they cause when reloading
2. Deleting local references to gradients and model weights within the code to reduce the overall load on the CPU memory
3. Resetting the model weights that Stable Embeddings assign within the optimizer here: https://github.com/bitsandbytes-foundation/bitsandbytes/blob/main/bitsandbytes/nn/modules.py#L96 before reloading the model to prevent it from incremently increasing the GPU RAM usage each reload

This week we ironed out a few critical bugs on feature/diloco that take us very close to merging it into main. These include:

- Building a fix for OOM errors that arrise when loading a global model that has a different architecture to a miner's local model
- Fixing errors in the state loader that where causing AllReduce rounds to fail if there where mismatches in model shapes across different miners
- Upgrading our Train scoring to reward miners for training on more rows of data in-between validation intervals
- Re-introducing bandwidth scoring
- Setting up train tracks for a more efficient AllReduce scoring mechanism that will reward miners for averaging more tensors each validation round

@distributed・38  We've just released  https://github.com/KMFODA/DistributedTraining/tree/feature/diloco to take us up from v0.4.6 to v1.0.0. This change does the following:
- It enables miners to have diverging local model states which they upload to HF every 15 minutes
- It asks validators to evaluate miners' local states against the datasets they trained on
- It pushes miners to share and average their pseudo gradients (i.e. the differences in their model states) every 3600 blocks using an AllReduce operation to bring all miners back to the same global model state
- It rewards miners based on how much data they train on and their success rate in AllReduce operations with an equal weighting

To get started miner's can follow the instructions in the README.md file as usual: https://github.com/KMFODA/DistributedTraining/blob/main/README.md. The main difference now from the previous setup is that miners have to:

> 3. Log their huggingface token on their VM:

> 4. Create a unique huggignface repo_id via the following link: https://huggingface.co/new and provide this repo_id under the config `neuron.local_model_name` in the startup command

Validators are able to get started using the same commands as before.

@distributed・38 we've just merged https://github.com/KMFODA/DistributedTraining/pull/60 to take us up to `v1.0.14` and we've launched a new training run to take us up to `run_4`. This PR does the following:

1. Converts train_score from a cummilative score to a point in time score. We believe this should help improve correlation amongst Non-WC validators and in turn hopefully reduce WCs VTrust.
2. Loads the global optimiser state if the local state is corrupted.
3. Resets a model after an AllReduce if NaNs are detected in it's loss.
4. Cancels the model upload process if an AllReduce is received since we noticed that some miners where failing AllReduces if they received them whilst they where uploading their latest model state.

Miners / Validators that aren't running with auto-updates please update to this latest version as soon as you can.
